# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gorilla-mux-go
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A **router** is a computer and networking device that forwards data packets between computer networks, including internetworks such as the global Internet.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Routers perform the *traffic directing* functions on the Internet.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A router is connected to two or more data lines from different IP networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] When a data packet comes in on a line, the router reads the network address information in the packet header to determine the ultimate destination.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Then, using information in its routing table or routing policy, it directs the packet to the next network on its journey.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A data packet is forwarded from one router to another through an internetwork until it reaches its destination node.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The most familiar type of IP routers are home and small office routers that forward IP packets between the home computers and the Internet.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] More sophisticated routers, such as enterprise routers, connect large business or ISP networks to powerful core routers that forward data at high speed along the optical fiber lines of the Internet backbone.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Routers can be built from standard computer parts but are mostly specialized purpose-built computers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Early routers used software-based forwarding, running on a CPU.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] More sophisticated devices use application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) to increase performance or add advanced filtering and firewall functionality.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The concepts of a *switching node* using software and an *interface computer* were first proposed by Donald Davies in 1966 for the NPL network.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The same idea was conceived by Wesley Clark the following year for use in the ARPANET, which were named *Interface Message Processors* (IMPs).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] These computers had fundamentally the same functionality as a router does today.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The idea for a router (called a *gateway* at the time) initially came about through an international group of computer networking researchers called the International Network Working Group (INWG).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] These gateway devices were different from most previous packet switching schemes in two ways.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] First, they connected dissimilar kinds of networks, such as serial lines and local area networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Second, they were connectionless devices, which had no role in assuring that traffic was delivered reliably, leaving that function entirely to the hosts.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] This particular idea, the end-to-end principle, was contained in the work of Donald Davies.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The concept was explored in practice by various groups, with the intention to produce a working system for internetworking.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] There were three notable contemporaneous programs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The first was an implementation directed by Louis Pouzin of the CYCLADES network, which was designed and developed during 1972-3.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The second was a program at Xerox PARC to explore new networking technologies, which produced the PARC Universal Packet system.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Some time after early 1974, the first Xerox routers became operational.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Due to corporate intellectual property concerns, it received little attention outside Xerox for years.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The third was a DARPA-initiated program, which began during 1973-4.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] This drew on the work of the other two programs, expanded significantly, and went on to create the TCP/IP architecture in use today.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] University College London (UCL) provided a gateway between British research groups and the ARPANET from 1973 until the late 1980s, latterly using SATNET.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The first true IP router was developed by Ginny Travers at BBN, as part of that DARPA-initiated effort, during 1975–1976.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] By the end of 1976, three PDP-11-based routers were in service in the experimental prototype Internet.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Mike Brecia, Ginny Travers, and Bob Hinden received the IEEE Internet Award for early IP routers in 2008.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The first multiprotocol routers were independently created by staff researchers at MIT and Stanford in 1981 and both were also based on PDP-11s.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Stanford's router program was led by William Yeager and MIT's by Noel Chiappa.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Virtually all networking now uses TCP/IP, but multiprotocol routers are still manufactured.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] They were important in the early stages of the growth of computer networking when protocols other than TCP/IP were in use.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Modern routers that handle both IPv4 and IPv6 are multiprotocol but are simpler devices than those that process AppleTalk, DECnet, IPX, and Xerox protocols.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] From the mid-1970s and in the 1980s, general-purpose minicomputers served as routers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Modern high-speed routers are network processors or highly specialized computers with extra hardware acceleration added to speed both common routing functions, such as packet forwarding, and specialized functions such as IPsec encryption.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] There is substantial use of Linux and Unix software-based machines, running open source routing code, for research and other applications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The Cisco IOS operating system was independently designed.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Major router operating systems, such as Junos and NX-OS, are extensively modified versions of Unix software.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] When multiple routers are used in interconnected networks, the routers can exchange information about destination addresses using a routing protocol.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Each router builds up a routing table, a list of routes, between two computer systems on the interconnected networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A router may have interfaces for multiple types of physical layer connections, such as copper cables, fiber optic, or wireless transmission.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] It can also support multiple network layer transmission standards.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Each network interface is used to enable data packets to be forwarded from one transmission system to another.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Routers may also be used to connect two or more logical groups of computer devices known as subnets, each with a unique network prefix.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Routers may provide connectivity within enterprises, between enterprises and the Internet, or between internet service providers' (ISPs') networks; they are also responsible for directing data between different networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The largest routers (such as the Cisco CRS-1 or Juniper PTX) interconnect the various ISPs, or may be used in large enterprise networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Smaller routers usually provide connectivity for typical home and office networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] All sizes of routers may be found inside enterprises.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The most powerful routers are usually found in ISPs, academic and research facilities.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Large businesses may also need more powerful routers to cope with ever-increasing demands of intranet data traffic.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A hierarchical internetworking model for interconnecting routers in large networks is in common use.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Some routers can connect to Data service units for T1 connections via serial ports.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The hierarchical internetworking model divides enterprise networks into three layers: core, distribution, and access.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Access routers, including small office/home office (SOHO) models, are located at home and customer sites such as branch offices that do not need hierarchical routing of their own.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Typically, they are optimized for low cost.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Some SOHO routers are capable of running alternative free Linux-based firmware like Tomato, OpenWrt, or DD-WRT.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Distribution routers aggregate traffic from multiple access routers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Distribution routers are often responsible for enforcing quality of service across a wide area network (WAN), so they may have considerable memory installed, multiple WAN interface connections, and substantial onboard data processing routines.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] They may also provide connectivity to groups of file servers or other external networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] In enterprises, a core router may provide a collapsed backbone interconnecting the distribution tier routers from multiple buildings of a campus, or large enterprise locations.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] They tend to be optimized for high bandwidth but lack some of the features of edge routers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] External networks must be carefully considered as part of the overall security strategy of the local network.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A router may include a firewall, VPN handling, and other security functions, or they may be handled by separate devices.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Routers also commonly perform network address translation, which restricts connections initiated from external connections but is not recognized as a security feature by all experts.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Some experts argue that open source routers are more secure and reliable than closed source routers because errors and potentially exploitable vulnerabilities are more likely to be discovered and addressed in an open-source environment.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Routers are also often distinguished on the basis of the network in which they operate.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A router in a local area network (LAN) of a single organization is called an *interior router*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A router that is operated in the Internet backbone is described as *exterior router*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] While a router that connects a LAN with the Internet or a wide area network (WAN) is called a *border router*, or *gateway router*.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Routers intended for ISP and major enterprise connectivity usually exchange routing information using the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Wi-Fi routers combine the functions of a router, switch and a wireless access point.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] They are typically devices with a small form factor, operating on the standard electric power supply for residential use.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Connected to the Internet as offered by an Internet service provider, they provide Internet access through Ethernet and Wi-Fi for home or office use.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The main purpose of a router is to connect multiple networks and forward packets destined either for directly attached networks or more remote networks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A router is considered a layer-3 device because its primary forwarding decision is based on the information in the layer-3 IP packet, specifically the destination IP address.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] When a router receives a packet, it searches its routing table to find the best match between the destination IP address of the packet and one of the addresses in the routing table.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Once a match is found, the packet is encapsulated in the layer-2 data link frame for the outgoing interface indicated in the table entry.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A router typically does not look into the packet payload, but only at the layer-3 addresses to make a forwarding decision, plus optionally other information in the header for hints on, for example, quality of service (QoS).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] For pure IP forwarding, a router is designed to minimize the state information associated with individual packets.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Once a packet is forwarded, the router does not retain any historical information about the packet.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The routing table itself can contain information derived from a variety of sources, such as a default or static routes that are configured manually, or dynamic entries from routing protocols where the router learns routes from other routers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] A default route is one that is used to route all traffic whose destination does not otherwise appear in the routing table; it is common – even necessary – in small networks, such as a home or small business, where the default route simply sends all non-local traffic to the Internet service provider.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] The default route can be manually configured (as a static route); learned by dynamic routing protocols; or be obtained by DHCP.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Besides deciding to which interface a packet is forwarded, which is handled primarily via the routing table, a router also has to manage congestion when packets arrive at a rate higher than the router can process.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Three policies commonly used are tail drop, random early detection (RED), and weighted random early detection (WRED).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Tail drop is the simplest and most easily implemented: the router simply drops new incoming packets once buffer space in the router is exhausted.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] RED probabilistically drops datagrams early when the queue exceeds a pre-configured portion of the buffer, until reaching a pre-determined maximum, when it drops all incoming packets, thus reverting to tail drop.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] WRED can be configured to drop packets more readily depending on the type of traffic.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Another function a router performs is traffic classification and deciding which packet should be processed first.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] This is managed through QoS, which is critical when Voice over IP is deployed, so as not to introduce excessive latency.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Yet another function a router performs is called policy-based routing, where special rules are constructed to override the rules derived from the routing table when a packet forwarding decision is made.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Some of the functions may be performed through an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) to avoid the overhead of scheduling CPU time to process the packets.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/router-computing] Others may have to be performed through the CPU as these packets need special attention that cannot be handled by an ASIC.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Search engines employ URI normalization to correctly rank pages that may be found with multiple URIs, and to reduce indexing of duplicate pages.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Web crawlers perform URI normalization to avoid crawling the same resource more than once.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Web browsers may perform normalization to determine if a link has been visited or to determine if a page has been cached.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Web servers may also perform normalization for many reasons (i.e. to be able to more easily intercept security risks coming from client requests, to use only one absolute file name for each resource stored in their caches, named in log files, etc.).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Several types of normalization may be performed.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Some of them are always semantics preserving and some may not be.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] However, there is no way to know if a URI path component represents a directory or not.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] RFC 3986 notes that if the former URI redirects to the latter URI, then that is an indication that they are equivalent.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] applications frequently use the value in the fragment.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] However, the order of parameters in a URI may be significant (this is not defined by the standard) and a web server may allow the same variable to appear multiple times.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Note that a parameter without a value is not necessarily an unused parameter.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] Some normalization rules may be developed for specific websites by examining URI lists obtained from previous crawls or web server logs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] we may assume that the two URIs are equivalent and can be normalized to one of the URI forms.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] (2006) present a heuristic called DustBuster for detecting DUST (different URIs with similar text) rules that can be applied to URI lists.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/url-normalization] They showed that once the correct DUST rules were found and applied with a normalization algorithm, they were able to find up to 68% of the redundant URIs in a URI list.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:gorilla-mux-go/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
